IDOR — Insecure Direct Object Reference
What It Is
IDOR happens when an application exposes a reference to an internal object — a database ID, a filename, an account number — and doesn't verify 
whether the requesting user actually has permission to access it.
The server trusts the value in the request. If you change it, you get someone else's data.
That's it. Simple concept, massive impact.

How It Looks in the Wild
Numeric IDs in URLs
GET /api/invoices/1084
Change 1084 to 1083, 1085, 1000 — if the server returns another user's invoice without checking ownership, it's vulnerable.
GUIDs / UUIDs
Some developers assume UUIDs are secure because they're hard to guess. They're not a security control — they're just long IDs.
GET /api/files/3f7a1c2d-9e4b-41fa-b8c3-0e2d5f6a7b1e
If you find one UUID (from a response, a link, a notification), you can test if others are accessible. GUIDs found in emails, shared links, or API responses are fair game.
Object References in POST Bodies
jsonPOST /api/messages/send
{
  "to_user_id": 2291,
  "message": "hey"
}
What happens if you change to_user_id to 1? Can you message users you shouldn't reach? Can you trigger actions on behalf of other accounts?
File Downloads
GET /download?file=report_user_2291.pdf
Try:
GET /download?file=report_user_2290.pdf
GET /download?file=../config/settings.ini
File-based IDORs often lead directly to sensitive document access or path traversal.
API Endpoints with Encoded References
Sometimes the ID is base64-encoded or hashed — don't let that stop you. Decode it, modify it, re-encode.
eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjogMjI5MX0=  →  {"user_id": 2291}  →  {"user_id": 1}  →  eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjogMX0=

Testing Methodology
Step 1 — Create Two Accounts
Always test with two separate accounts (attacker and victim). This gives you:

Victim's object references
Attacker's session to replay requests with

Step 2 — Map All Object References
While browsing normally, note every ID, reference, or identifier that appears in:

URLs
Request bodies (JSON/form data)
Response bodies
Headers (e.g., X-User-ID)

Step 3 — Swap References Across Sessions
Use Burp's Repeater with the attacker's session cookies, but plug in the victim's object IDs. If you get a 200 OK with data, you've found an IDOR.
Step 4 — Test All HTTP Methods
An endpoint might enforce access control on GET but not on PUT, DELETE, or PATCH.
GET  /api/user/2291/profile   → 403 Forbidden ✓
PUT  /api/user/2291/profile   → 200 OK        ✗ (IDOR on write)
DELETE /api/user/2291/profile → 200 OK        ✗ (IDOR on delete)
Step 5 — Check Indirect References
Some apps use indirect references in one place but expose the direct reference in another (e.g., a download endpoint that reveals the real filename in the response).

