Real Example (Sanitized)
Target: A SaaS project management app
Endpoint: GET /api/v1/projects/{project_id}/export
Finding: Project IDs were sequential integers. Authenticated users could export any project by incrementing the ID — including projects from other organizations.
Impact: Full data exfiltration across tenant boundaries (critical in a multi-tenant SaaS).
Fix: Server-side check that project.organization_id == current_user.organization_id before returning export.

Remediation
The fix is always the same: enforce authorization server-side on every request.

Never trust object references sent by the client
Always verify the requesting user owns or has permission to access the object
Use indirect reference maps where possible (map session-scoped tokens to real IDs server-side)
Apply access control checks in a centralized layer — not scattered across individual endpoints

python# Wrong
def get_invoice(invoice_id):
    return db.query(Invoice).filter_by(id=invoice_id).first()

# Right
def get_invoice(invoice_id, current_user):
    invoice = db.query(Invoice).filter_by(id=invoice_id).first()
    if invoice.user_id != current_user.id:
        raise PermissionDenied()
    return invoice

